= Papen's Scheme Reaches a Dead End

Despite Oskar and Meissner’s willingness to entertain Papen’s schemes to end the political deadlock, Schleicher’s strengthened position has made it harder to instill a sense of urgency in Hindenburg—at least enough to convince him to do the impossible. Papen, meanwhile, refuses to abandon his demand for the chancellorship, arguing that the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazis</span> are quickly collapsing and that he, not they, should be the senior partner.

A furious [+ nsdap_leader +] has rejected Papen’s call for a meeting between his movement and the Camarilla, and negotiations have since collapsed. Although Papen’s desire for revenge against Schleicher remains undimmed, he increasingly sees [+ nsdap_chancellor +]’s appointment as impossible—and himself as the only viable alternative. A belief that [+ nsdap_leader +] refuses to believe in.

